You know how to parse it,
encode it, decode it.

00:14:02.330 --> 00:14:06.650
So it looks like, on the
programming side you know what

00:14:06.650 --> 00:14:07.790
needs to be done.

00:14:07.790 --> 00:14:10.220
Now the problem is, why
aren't you getting

00:14:10.220 --> 00:14:12.450
back the call back?

00:14:12.450 --> 00:14:16.160
So the first thing to check is
on the client side handler

00:14:16.160 --> 00:14:18.020
check the error code return.

00:14:18.020 --> 00:14:20.330
And I believe it should
be postback error.

00:14:20.330 --> 00:14:22.830
That's what--

00:14:22.830 --> 00:14:24.080
you're getting--

00:14:32.470 --> 00:14:33.380
try--

00:14:33.380 --> 00:14:35.750
the postback, it just did not
receive back the confirmation.

00:14:35.750 --> 00:14:39.060
So somewhere along the
way something broke.

00:14:39.060 --> 00:14:44.050
Check that you're not
behind a login wall.

00:14:44.050 --> 00:14:47.240
In a lot of cases Google App
Engine, when you create an

00:14:47.240 --> 00:14:50.260
account, it has restriction who
can post to your site, so

00:14:50.260 --> 00:14:52.330
sometimes you are behind
a login wall.

00:14:52.330 --> 00:14:53.900
And then the call
back gets lost.

00:14:53.900 --> 00:14:57.820
So check your logs, see what's
happening there.

00:14:57.820 --> 00:15:03.220
PENG YING: One easy way to
test is to actually curl

00:15:03.220 --> 00:15:06.190
content to your postback
handler, or to your web

00:15:06.190 --> 00:15:07.660
service handler.

00:15:07.660 --> 00:15:09.530
So that way you can just do
something from terminal.

00:15:09.530 --> 00:15:12.185
You type in curl, the data
you want to send

00:15:12.185 --> 00:15:13.285
over, and the URL.

00:15:13.285 --> 00:15:14.810
And that'll just post it.

00:15:14.810 --> 00:15:16.220
MIHAI IONESCU: Right, so
simulate what Google

00:15:16.220 --> 00:15:18.410
is doing in a way.

00:15:18.410 --> 00:15:21.070
And make sure you can
handle that case.

00:15:21.070 --> 00:15:24.430
And then, of course, there is
the 10 second delay issue.

00:15:24.430 --> 00:15:28.740
Even though that's a pretty long
delay, who knows what may

00:15:28.740 --> 00:15:30.620
happen on your server side.

00:15:30.620 --> 00:15:32.600
Make sure, if you get
a call back, you

00:15:32.600 --> 00:15:35.200
respond within 10 seconds.

00:15:35.200 --> 00:15:37.800
And then the order
will go through.

00:15:37.800 --> 00:15:41.800
Then you'll receive the correct
confirmation on the

00:15:41.800 --> 00:15:45.470
client side and then the
transaction is complete.

